history.content:
I would not do that unless you have extensive math experience (AP calc/community college multivariable doesn't count). First of all, most times lower divs like 16a will get everyone off the waitlist so you will likely be able to take it. Second, 70 is a hard time consuming class. You need a lot of mathematical maturity to do well in it, and it will eat a lot of time. It's also your first semester in college - you have to get used to college life, college classes, and also have a little fun.

Look at the materials at eecs70.org. If you read through the notes and understand them yourself (perhaps with some googling) without extensive help, then you'll most likely be fine.

children.subject:
Hi , how smart do you consider your roommate , like is he average? I have prior programming experience and am generally good at maths.

    Thanks

Can you describe what you mean by “generally good”? My roommate did have a little math competition experience. The best thing to do is look at the curriculum beforehand and some homework and see if you will be able to solve the questions.
Its completely fine. My roomate did it and it wasn’t hard for him.
